         "date": "01 June 2022 10:50",
         "html": "<p>Regarding &quot;It could also try to restart LACP using a different system ID hoping that the remote nodes don&rsquo;t get confused, but I have yet to see an implementation that would go that far.&quot;</p>\n\n<p>The Cumulus Linux MLAG implementation is documented to do this in some peer link failure scenarios:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://docs.nvidia.com/networking-ethernet-software/knowledge-base/Configuration-and-Usage/Network-Interfaces/MLAG-Redundancy-Scenarios/#scenario-1-peer-link-failure-clagd-backup-ip-is-active\">Scenario 1: Peer Link Failure, clagd-backup-ip Is Active</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://docs.nvidia.com/networking-ethernet-software/knowledge-base/Configuration-and-Usage/Network-Interfaces/MLAG-Redundancy-Scenarios/#scenario-2-peer-link-failure-clagd-backup-ip-is-not-active\">Scenario 2: Peer Link Failure, clagd-backup-ip Is not Active</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://docs.nvidia.com/networking-ethernet-software/knowledge-base/Configuration-and-Usage/Network-Interfaces/MLAG-Redundancy-Scenarios/#scenario-4-primary-power-off-clagd-backup-ip-is-not-active\">Scenario 4: Primary Power Off, clagd-backup-ip Is not Active</a></li>\n</ul>\n",
